# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: d-vhs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:d-vhs/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:d-vhs/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:d-vhs/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:d-vhs/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] 1080p video signals are supported by ATSC standards in the United States and DVB standards in Europe.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Applications of the 1080p standard include television broadcasts, Blu-ray Discs, smartphones, Internet content such as YouTube videos and Netflix TV shows and movies, consumer-grade televisions and projectors, computer monitors and video game consoles.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Small camcorders, smartphones and digital cameras can capture still and moving images in 1080p resolution.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept a 1080p signal and display it with a native resolution of at least 1080 lines vertically (as well as the ability to upscale lower-resolution material to 1080p).
[src:d-vhs/1080p] This means that the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] The HD ready 1080p logo program, by DigitalEurope, requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 25 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning frames per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second was being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition, although 24 fps was used for shooting movies.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Most current revisions of SMPTE 372M, SMPTE 424M and EBU Tech 3299 require YCbCr color space and 4:2:2 chroma subsampling for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08 Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] In the United States, the original ATSC standards for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as **1080p24**, **1080p25** and **1080p30**).
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Such frame rates require H.264/AVC *High Profile Level 4.2*, while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient MPEG-2 codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for subchannels.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] In Europe, 1080p25 signals have been supported by the DVB suite of broadcasting standards.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] The 1080p50 format is considered to be a future-proof production format and, eventually, a future broadcasting format.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] 1080p50 broadcasting should require the same bandwidth as 1080i50 signal and only 15–20% more than that of 720p50 signal due to increased compression efficiency, though 1080p50 production requires more bandwidth or more efficient codecs such as JPEG 2000, high-bitrate MPEG-2, or H.264/AVC and HEVC.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] EBU requires that legacy MPEG-4 AVC decoders should avoid crashing in the presence of SVC or 1080p50 (and higher resolution) packets.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] The ITU-T BT.2100 standard that includes Advanced 1080p video was subsequently published in July 2016.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] In practice, 1080p typically refers to a 1920 × 1080p raster with a 16:9 picture aspect ratio.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] The following is a list of other resolutions with a picture height of 1080 lines that are sometimes referred as 1080p.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] In the United States, 1080p over-the-air broadcasts are currently available in select stations in some cities in the US via ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations where as ATSC 3.0 is currently rolling out throughout the U.S.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] The majority of the stations that broadcast at 1080p are CBS and NBC stations and affiliates.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] All other stations do not broadcast at 1080p and usually broadcast at 720p60 (including when simulcasting in ATSC 3.0) or 1080i60 (outside of ATSC 3.0) encoded with MPEG-2.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] There is also technical restrictions with ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations that prevent stations from airing at 1080p.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] While converting to ATSC 3.0 is voluntary by TV Stations, there is no word when any of the major networks will consider airing at 1080p in the foreseeable future on a national scale, although they are required to broadcast ATSC signals for at least five years thereafter.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] However, satellite services (e.g., DirecTV, XstreamHD and Dish Network) use the 1080p/24-30 format with MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 encoding for pay-per-view movies that are downloaded in advance via satellite or on-demand via broadband.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] For material that originates from a progressive scanned 24 frame/s source (such as film), MPEG-2 lets the video be coded as 1080p24, irrespective of the final output format.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] These progressively-coded frames are tagged with metadata (literally, fields of the PICTURE header) instructing a decoder how to perform a 3:2 pulldown to interlace them.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] While the formal output of the MPEG-2 decoding process from such stations is 1080i60, the actual content is coded as 1080p24 and can be viewed as such (using a process known as inverse telecine) since no information is lost even when the broadcaster performs the 3:2 pulldown.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] In June 2016, German television stations began broadcasting 1080p50 high-definition video on eight channels via the HEVC-encoded DVB-T2 protocol.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] A total of 40 channels were available on March 29, 2017 (Phase 1).
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Blu-ray Discs are able to hold 1080p HD content, and most movies released on Blu-ray Disc produce a full 1080p HD picture when the player is connected to a 1080p HDTV via an HDMI cable.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Generally this type of video runs at 30 to 40 megabits per second, compared to the 3.5 megabits per second for conventional standard definition broadcasts.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Smartphones with 1080p Full HD display have been available on the market since 2012.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] As of 2014, it is the standard for mid-range to high-end smartphones, with many flagship devices using even higher resolutions, such as Quad HD (1440p) or Ultra HD (2160p).
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Several websites, including YouTube, allow videos to be uploaded in the 1080p format.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] YouTube streams 1080p content at approximately 4 megabits per second compared to Blu-ray's 30 to 40 megabits per second.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Digital distribution services like Hulu and HBO Max also deliver 1080p content, such as movies available on Blu-ray Disc or from broadcast sources.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] This can include distribution services like peer-to-peer websites and public or private tracking networks.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Netflix has been offering high quality 1080p content in the US and other countries through select internet providers since 2013.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] As of 2012, most consumer televisions being sold provide 1080p inputs, mainly via HDMI, and support full high-definition resolutions.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] 1080p resolution is available in all types of television, including plasma, LCD, DLP front and rear projection and LCD projection.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] For displaying film-based 1080i60 signals, a scheme called 3:2 pulldown reversal (reverse telecine) is beginning to appear in some newer 1080p displays, which can produce a true 1080p quality image from film-based 1080i60 programs.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Similarly, 25fps content broadcast at 1080i50 may be deinterlaced to 1080p content with no loss of quality or resolution.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] AV equipment manufacturers have adopted the term *Full HD* to mean a set can display all available HD resolutions up to 1080p.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] The term is misleading, however, because it does not guarantee the set is capable of rendering digital video at all frame rates encoded in source files with 1920 X 1080 pixel resolution.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Most notably, a "Full HD" set is not guaranteed to support the 1080p24 format, leading to consumer confusion.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] DigitalEurope (formerly EICTA) maintains the HD ready 1080p logo program that requires the certified TV sets to support 1080p24, 1080p50, and 1080p60, without overscan/underscan and picture distortion.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Most widescreen cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors can natively display 1080p content.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] For example, widescreen WUXGA monitors support 1920 × 1200 resolution, which can display a pixel for pixel reproduction of the 1080p (1920 × 1080) format.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Additionally, many 23, 24, and 27-inch (690 mm) widescreen LCD monitors use 1920 × 1200 as their native resolution; 30 inch displays can display beyond 1080p at up to 2560 × 1600 (1600p).
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Many 27" monitors have native resolutions of 2560 × 1440 and hence operate at 1440p.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Sony has their first and formerly Vaio 1080p laptop, VPCCB17FG, in 2011, and since Asus also has their first 4K laptop GL502 which was formerly branded Republic of Gamers in 2017, 1080p has also become the nowadays lowest standard for laptops.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] While Microsoft's original Xbox, launched as part of the sixth generation of video game consoles in 2001, could support a 1080i output in limited circumstances, support for 1080p began with the launch of the seventh generation of home video game consoles in 2005.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Both the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 were capable of outputting at 1080p, with only the Wii unable to support the resolution.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] All home video game consoles launched as part of the eighth generation, which began in 2012 with the launch of the Wii U, were capable of 1080p outputs.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Mid-generation hardware revisions and new models introduced by Sony and Microsoft to their respective PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles added the capability of outputting at 4K UHD — well beyond 1080p.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Moreover, this mid-generational improvement in computing power also represented a leap in the ability of video game consoles to render gaming content at a 1080p resolution or higher, rather than relying on upscaling.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] This trend continued with the launch of the current ninth generation of video game consoles in 2020, in which both Sony's PlayStation 5 and Microsoft's Xbox Series X were advertised as including 8K UHD support.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] As of 2024, however, neither console yet supports outputting the standard and PlayStation 5 packaging no longer advertises the feature.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] The Nintendo Switch console displays in resolutions up to 1080p when docked, while the successor console, Nintendo Switch 2, displays in 1080p when undocked, and up to 4K when docked.
[src:d-vhs/1080p] Many cameras—professional and consumer still, action and video cameras, including DSLR cameras—and other devices with built-in cameras such as laptops, smartphones and tablet computers, can capture 1080p24, 1080p25, 1080p30 or 1080p60 video, often encoding it in progressive segmented frame format.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] 1440p video mastered from 4:3 ratio content can be displayed with 1920×1440 or higher resolution such as QXGA or 2304×1440 with scaling, windowboxing, or pillarboxing.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] Widescreen 16:9 aspect ratio 1440p requires 2560×1440 (WQHD) resolution, possible with WQXGA, 2560×1920, or higher resolution with letterboxing, scaling, or windowboxing.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] The HDMI 1.3 specification supports WQXGA, and hence widescreen 1440p.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] Early 1440p computer displays became commonly available in 2010.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] Dell's UltraSharp U2711 monitor was released in 2010 as WQHD, with a 1440p widescreen.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] The 27-inch Apple LED Cinema Display released in 2010 also had a native resolution of 2560 × 1440, as did the Apple Thunderbolt Display which was sold from July 2011 to June 2016.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] MacBook with Retina Display (2012) is also one of the earliest laptops that utilise 1440p widescreen.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] By 2020, 1440p had expanded to a common resolution for computer gaming, with multiple video cards available that supported high frame rates at that resolution.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] In early 2021, QHD gaming laptops with fast refresh rates were introduced by multiple computer manufacturers.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] According to Steam's July 2024 Hardware & Software Survey, the resolution 2560 x 1440 has increased in overall usage on Steam by ~0.7% from May 2024, totaling to ~20% of its total userbase.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] In relation to smartphones, 1440p displays are sometimes marketed as "Quad HD", as it is four times the resolution of 720p high definition.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] The Vivo Xplay 3S, released December 2013, was the first smartphone to use a 1440p display; by 2015, 1440p had seen wider adoption by high-end flagship smartphones from major companies.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] An example of a smartphone with a 1440p display is the 1st generation Google Pixel XL.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] In September 2020, Microsoft revealed the Xbox Series S would support a resolution of 1440p at 120 FPS.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] In July 2022, Sony added 1440p support for the PlayStation 5.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] In April 2025, Nintendo revealed the Nintendo Switch 2 would support a resolution of 1440p at 120 FPS output via HDMI when playing in TV mode.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] The label "2K" is sometimes used to refer to 2560 × 1440 (commonly known as 1440p).
[src:d-vhs/1440p] This is inconsistent with "4K" denoting approximately 4,000 horizontal pixels, which makes 1920 or 2048 pixels wide the closest to "2K", a label which predates the use of 2560 × 1440.
[src:d-vhs/1440p] Some sources and manufacturers prefer "2.5K" as a term for 2560 × 1440 to avoid this confusion, and there is a similar "2.7K" (2720 × 1530) used by some drones, as well as a "2.8K" (2880 × 1620).
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] As of May 2025, 16K resolutions can be run in prototype displays, large public displays or using multi-monitor setups with AMD Eyefinity, or Nvidia Surround or Mosaic Technology.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] In early 2014, Japanese companies Nest+Visual, Sony and Indy Associates produced the first 16K film, using a Sony F65 CineAlta camera equipped with an anamorphic lens.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] The film was presented in March 2014 on a multi-screen video display at the Tokyo International Airport in Haneda, Japan.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] In 2016, AMD announced a target for their future graphics cards to support 16K resolution with a refresh rate of 240 Hz for "true immersion" in VR.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] Linus Tech Tips released a series of videos in 2017 attempting to play video games at 16K using sixteen 4K monitors.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] In 2018, US filmmaker Martin Lisius released a short time-lapse film titled, "Prairie Wind" that he produced using a 2-camera Canon EOS 5DS system he developed.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] Two still images were stitched together to create one 15985 × 5792 pixel image and then rendered as 16K resolution video with an extremely wide aspect ratio of 2.76∶1.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] This is among the first known 16K videos to exist.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] Innolux displayed the world's first 100-inch 16K (15360 × 8640) display module at Touch Taiwan in August 2018.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] Sony introduced a 64 by 18 foot (19.5 m × 5.5 m) commercial 16K display at NAB 2019 that is set to be released in Japan.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] It is made up of 576 modules (each 360 × 360) in a formation of 48 by 12 modules, forming a 17280 × 4320 screen with a 4∶1 aspect ratio.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] On June 26, 2019, VESA formally released the DisplayPort 2.0 standard with support for one 16K (15360 × 8640-pixel) display supporting 30-bit-per-pixel 4:4:4 RGB/Y′CBCR-color HDR video at a refresh rate of 60 Hz using DSC video compression.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] Sphere, an entertainment venue located in Las Vegas, Nevada, opened with a wraparound interior LED screen on September 29, 2023.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] According to Sphere Entertainment, the screen within the theater is 160,000 sq ft (15,000 m2) and supports a 16K (16000 × 16000-pixel) resolution, making it the highest resolution LED screen in the world.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] At "Display Week" 2023, Chinese manufacturer BOE unveiled the world's first 110-inch 16K consumer television.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] The LCD-based screen outputs a native resolution of 15360×8640 pixels, which is four times the pixel count of 8K and sixteen times that of 4K.
[src:d-vhs/16k-resolution] Operating at a 60 Hz refresh rate, the television delivers a brightness of 400 nits and a contrast ratio of 1200:1.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] For 90 years, 20th Century has been one of the major American film studios.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It was founded on May 31, 1935, by the merger of Fox Film Corporation and Twentieth Century Pictures, and was one of the original "Big Five" among eight majors of Hollywood's Golden Age.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 1985, it was acquired by Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, which was renamed 21st Century Fox in 2013 after it spun off its publishing assets.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Disney purchased most of 21st Century Fox's assets, which included 20th Century Fox, on March 20, 2019.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The studio adopted its current name on January 17, 2020, in order to avoid confusion with Fox Corporation, and subsequently started to use it for the copyright of 20th Century and Searchlight Pictures productions on December 4.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] 20th Century is currently one of five live-action film studios within the Walt Disney Studios, alongside Walt Disney Pictures, Marvel Studios, Lucasfilm, and its sister speciality unit, Searchlight Pictures.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] 20th Century also releases animated films produced by its animation division, 20th Century Animation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Twentieth Century Pictures' Joseph Schenck and Darryl F.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Zanuck left United Artists over a stock dispute, and began merger talks with the management of financially struggling Fox Film, under President Sidney Kent.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Spyros Skouras, then manager of the Fox West Coast Theaters, helped make it happen (and later became president of the new company).
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The company had been struggling since founder William Fox lost control of the company in 1930.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox Film Corporation and Twentieth Century Pictures merged in 1935.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Initially, it was speculated in *The New York Times* that the newly merged company would be named "Fox-Twentieth Century".
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The new company, Twentieth Century-Fox Film Corporation, began trading on May 31, 1935.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Kent remained at the company, joining Schenck and Zanuck.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Zanuck replaced Winfield Sheehan as the company's production chief.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The company established a special training school.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Lynn Bari, Patricia Farr and Anne Nagel were among 14 young women "launched on the trail of film stardom" on August 6, 1935, when they each received a six-month contract with Twentieth Century-Fox after spending 18 months in the school.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The contracts included a studio option for renewal for as long as seven years.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] For many years, Twentieth Century-Fox identified themselves as having been founded in 1915, the year Fox Film was founded.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] For instance, it marked 1945 as its 30th anniversary.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] However, it has considered the 1935 merger as its founding in recent years, even though most film historians agree it was founded in 1915.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The company's films retained the Twentieth Century Pictures searchlight logo on their opening credits as well as its opening fanfare, but with the name changed to Twentieth Century-Fox.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After the merger was completed, Zanuck signed young actors to help carry Twentieth Century-Fox: Tyrone Power, Linda Darnell, Carmen Miranda, Don Ameche, Henry Fonda, Gene Tierney, Sonja Henie, and Betty Grable.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox also hired Alice Faye and Shirley Temple, who appeared in several major films for the studio in the 1930s.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Higher attendance during World War II helped Twentieth Century-Fox overtake RKO and Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer to become the third most profitable film studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 1941, Zanuck was commissioned as a lieutenant colonel in the U.S.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Signal Corps and assigned to supervise the production of U.S.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] His partner, William Goetz, filled in at Twentieth Century-Fox.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 1942, Spyros Skouras succeeded Kent as president of the studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] During the next few years, with pictures like *Wilson* (1944), *The Razor's Edge* (1946), *Boomerang*, *Gentleman's Agreement* (both 1947), *The Snake Pit* (1948), and *Pinky* (1949), Zanuck established a reputation for provocative, adult films.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox also specialized in adaptations of best-selling books such as Ben Ames Williams' *Leave Her to Heaven* (1945), starring Gene Tierney, which was the highest-grossing Twentieth Century-Fox film of the 1940s.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The studio also produced film versions of Broadway musicals, including the Rodgers and Hammerstein films, beginning with the musical version of *State Fair* (1945), the only work that the partnership wrote specially for films.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After the war, audiences slowly drifted away.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox held on to its theaters until a court-mandated "divorce"; they were spun off as Fox National Theaters in 1953.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] That year, with attendance at half the 1946 level, Twentieth Century-Fox gambled on an unproven process.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] President Spyros Skouras struck a deal with the inventor Henri Chrétien, leaving the other film studios empty-handed, and in 1953 introduced CinemaScope in the studio's groundbreaking feature film *The Robe*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Zanuck announced in February 1953 that henceforth all Twentieth Century-Fox pictures would be made in CinemaScope.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] To convince theater owners to install this new process, Twentieth Century-Fox agreed to help pay conversion costs (about $25,000 per screen); and to ensure enough product, Twentieth Century-Fox leased access to CinemaScope to any rival studio choosing to use it.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Seeing the box-office for the first two CinemaScope features, *The Robe* and *How to Marry a Millionaire* (also 1953), Warner Bros., MGM, RKO, Universal-International, Columbia, UA, Allied Artists, and Disney quickly adopted the process.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 1956, Twentieth Century-Fox engaged Robert Lippert to establish a subsidiary company, Regal Pictures, later Associated Producers Incorporated to film B pictures in CinemaScope (but "branded" RegalScope).
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox produced new musicals using the CinemaScope process including *Carousel* and *The King and I* (both 1956).
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] CinemaScope brought a brief upturn in attendance, but by 1956 the numbers again began to slide.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] That year Darryl Zanuck announced his resignation as head of production.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Zanuck moved to Paris, setting up as an independent producer, seldom being in the United States for many years.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In mid 1956, the company loaned the pre-1948 film library, including TV distribution rights, but not the copyrights of these films, to National Telefilm Associates for 10 years.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Zanuck's successor, producer Buddy Adler, died a year later.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] President Spyros Skouras brought in a series of production executives, but none had Zanuck's success.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] By the early 1960s, Twentieth Century-Fox was in trouble.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] A new version of *Cleopatra* (1963) began production in 1959 with Joan Collins in the lead.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] As a publicity gimmick, producer Walter Wanger offered $1 million to Elizabeth Taylor if she would star; she accepted and costs for *Cleopatra* began to escalate.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Richard Burton's on-set romance with Taylor was surrounding the media.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] However, Skouras' selfish preferences and inexperienced micromanagement on the film's production did nothing to speed up production on *Cleopatra*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Meanwhile, another remake—of the Cary Grant hit *My Favorite Wife* (1940)—was rushed into production in an attempt to turn over a quick profit to help keep Twentieth Century-Fox afloat.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The romantic comedy entitled *Something's Got to Give* paired Marilyn Monroe, Twentieth Century-Fox's most bankable star of the 1950s, with Dean Martin and director George Cukor.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The troubled Monroe caused delays daily, and it quickly descended into a costly debacle.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] As *Cleopatra*'s budget passed $10 million, eventually costing around $40 million, Twentieth Century-Fox sold its back lot (now the site of Century City) to Alcoa in 1961 to raise funds.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After several weeks of script rewrites on the Monroe picture and very little progress, mostly due to director George Cukor's filming methods, in addition to Monroe's chronic sinusitis, Monroe was fired from *Something's Got to Give* and two months later she was found dead.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] According to Twentieth Century-Fox files, she was rehired within weeks for a two-picture deal totaling $1 million, $500,000 to finish *Something's Got to Give* (plus a bonus at completion), and another $500,000 for *What a Way to Go*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Elizabeth Taylor's disruptive reign on the *Cleopatra* set continued unchallenged from 1960 into 1962, though three Twentieth Century-Fox executives went to Rome in June 1962 to fire her.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Mankiewicz had filmed out of sequence and had only done interiors, so Twentieth Century-Fox was then forced to allow Taylor several more weeks of filming.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In the meantime during that summer of 1962 Fox released nearly all of its contract stars to offset burgeoning costs, including Jayne Mansfield.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] With few pictures on the schedule, Skouras wanted to rush Zanuck's big-budget war epic *The Longest Day* (1962), an accurate account of the Allied invasion of Normandy on June 6, 1944, with a huge international cast, into release as another source of quick cash.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] This offended Zanuck, still Twentieth Century-Fox's largest shareholder, for whom *The Longest Day* was a labor of love that he had dearly wanted to produce for many years.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After it became clear that *Something's Got to Give* would not be able to progress without Monroe in the lead (Martin had refused to work with anyone else), Skouras finally decided that re-signing her was unavoidable.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] But days before filming was due to resume, she was found dead at her Los Angeles home and the picture resumed filming as *Move Over, Darling*, with Doris Day and James Garner in the leads.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The unfinished scenes from *Something's Got to Give* were shelved for nearly 40 years.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Rather than being rushed into release as if it were a B-picture, *The Longest Day* was lovingly and carefully produced under Zanuck's supervision.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It was finally released at a length of three hours and was well received.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] At the next board meeting, Zanuck spoke for eight hours, convincing directors that Skouras was mismanaging the company and that he was the only possible successor.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Zanuck was installed as chairman, and then named his son Richard Zanuck as president.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox also had two big science-fiction hits in the decade: *Fantastic Voyage* (1966), and the original *Planet of the Apes* (1968), starring Charlton Heston, Kim Hunter, and Roddy McDowall.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] *Fantastic Voyage* was the last film made in CinemaScope; the studio had held on to the format while Panavision lenses were being used elsewhere.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Zanuck stayed on as chairman until 1971, but there were several expensive flops in his last years, resulting in Twentieth Century-Fox posting losses from 1969 to 1971.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Following his removal and replacement by Dennis Stanfill as chairman, and after an uncertain period, new management brought Twentieth Century-Fox back to health.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Stulberg and production head Alan Ladd, Jr., Twentieth Century-Fox films connected with modern audiences.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Board chairman Dennis Stanfill used the profits to acquire resort properties, soft-drink bottlers, Australian theaters and other properties in an attempt to diversify enough to offset the boom-or-bust cycle of picture-making.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Foreshadowing a pattern of film production still yet to come, in late 1973 Twentieth Century-Fox partnered with Warner Bros. to co-produce *The Towering Inferno* (1974), an all-star action blockbuster from producer Irwin Allen.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Both studios found themselves owning the rights to books about burning skyscrapers.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Allen insisted on a meeting with the heads of both studios and announced that as Twentieth Century-Fox was already in the lead with their property it would be career suicide to have competing movies.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Thus the first joint-venture studio deal was struck.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In hindsight, while it may be commonplace now, back in the 1970s, it was a risky, but revolutionary, idea that paid off handsomely at both domestic and international box offices around the world.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Twentieth Century-Fox's success reached new heights by backing the most profitable film made up to that time, *Star Wars* (1977).
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Substantial financial gains were realized as a result of the film's unprecedented success: from a low of $6 in June 1976, stock prices more than quadrupled to almost $27 after *Star Wars* release; 1976 revenues of $195 million rose to $301 million in 1977.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] With financial stability came new owners, when 20th Century-Fox was sold for $720 million on June 8, 1981, to investors Marc Rich and Marvin Davis.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] 20th Century-Fox's assets included Pebble Beach Golf Links, the Aspen Skiing Company and a Century City property upon which Davis built and twice sold Fox Plaza.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] By 1984, Rich had become a fugitive from justice, having fled to Switzerland after being charged by U.S. federal prosecutors with tax evasion, racketeering and illegal trading with Iran during the Iran hostage crisis.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Rich's assets were frozen by U.S. authorities.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 1984, Marvin Davis bought out Marc Rich's 50% interest in 20th Century-Fox Film Corporation for an undisclosed amount, reported to be $116 million.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Davis sold this interest to Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation for $250 million in March 1985.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Davis later backed out of a deal with Murdoch to purchase John Kluge's Metromedia television stations.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Murdoch went ahead alone and bought the stations, and later bought out Davis' remaining stake in Twentieth Century-Fox for $325 million.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] From 1985, the hyphen was permanently deleted from the brand name, with *Twentieth Century-Fox* changing to *Twentieth Century Fox*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] To gain FCC approval of 20th Century-Fox's purchase of Metromedia's television holdings, once the stations of the long-dissolved DuMont network, Murdoch had to become a U.S. citizen.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] He did so in 1985, and in 1986 the new Fox Broadcasting Company took to the air.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Over the next 20-odd years the network and owned-stations group expanded to become extremely profitable for News Corporation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Then in 1993, 20th Century Fox bought the superhero rights to the X-Men, while the Fantastic Four was bought in 1998.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Then Bryan Singer directed the first film and the second film, while Brett Ratner was hired to direct the third film of the original trilogy.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 1994, 20th Century Fox would establish four new divisions: Fox Searchlight Pictures, Fox Family Films, Fox Animation Studios, and Fox 2000 Pictures.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox Searchlight would specialize in the specialty and indie film market, with Thomas Rothman, then president of production at The Samuel Goldwyn Company, being brought on to head up the new studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It was soon given its name with Rothman as its founding president.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox Family Films was tasked with producing films geared towards families, under John Matoian.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox Animation Studios was established on August 9, 1994, designed to compete with Walt Disney Feature Animation, whom had found success in the Disney Renaissance.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Don Bluth and Gary Goldman of the failing Sullivan Bluth Studios were appointed to head the new $100 million animation studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox 2000 Pictures was formed to specialize in mid-budget-ranging films targeted towards underserved groups of audiences, with Laura Ziskin brought on as president.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In November 1995, 20th Century Fox entered a $50 million agreement to purchase the library of bankrupt Carolco Pictures, which would have given Fox the rights to make a sequel based on the hit Carolco film *Terminator 2: Judgement Day*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] However, Fox dropped their bid in January 1996, after French company Canal+ submitted a $58 million counterbid for the assets.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In August 1997, Fox's Los Angeles-based visual effects company, VIFX, acquired majority interest in Blue Sky Studios to form a new visual effects and animation company, temporarily renamed "Blue Sky/VIFX".
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Blue Sky had previously did the character animation of MTV Films' first film *Joe's Apartment.*Following the studio's expansion, Blue Sky produced character animation for the films *Alien Resurrection*, *A Simple Wish*, *Mouse Hunt*, *Star Trek: Insurrection* and *Fight Club*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] VIFX was later sold to another VFX studio Rhythm and Hues Studios in March 1999.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] According to Blue Sky founder Chris Wedge, Fox considered selling Blue Sky as well by 2000 due to financial difficulties in the visual effects industry in general.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In February 1998, following the success of Fox Animation Studios' first film *Anastasia*, Fox Family Films changed its name to Fox Animation Studios and dropped its live action production. which would be picked up by other production units.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The actual Fox Animation Studios would become a division of the formerly-named Fox Family Films, being referred to as the Phoenix studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] However, Fox Animation Studios in Los Angeles would be renamed to 20th Century Fox Animation between 1998 and 1999.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The Phoenix studio would face financial problems, eventually with Fox laying off 300 of the nearly 380 people who worked at the Phoenix studio to "make films more efficiently".
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After the box-office failure of *Titan A.E.*, Fox Animation Studios would shut down on June 26, 2000.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Their last film set to be made would have been an adaptation of Wayne Barlowe's illustrated novel *Barlowe's Inferno*, and was set to be done entirely with computer animation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Another film they would have made was *The Little Beauty King*, an adult animated film directed by Steve Oedekerk, which would have been a satire of the films from the Disney Renaissance.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Chris Wedge, film producer Lori Forte, and Fox Animation executive Chris Meledandri presented Fox with a script for a comedy feature film titled *Ice Age*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Studio management pressured staff to sell their remaining shares and options to Fox on the promise of continued employment on feature-length films.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The studio moved to White Plains, New York and started production on *Ice Age*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] As the film wrapped, Fox, having little faith in the film, feared that it might bomb at the box office.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox terminated half of the production staff and tried unsuccessfully to find a buyer for the film and the studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Instead, *Ice Age* was released by Fox in conjunction with Twentieth Century Fox Animation on March 15, 2002, to critical and commercial success, receiving a nomination for an Academy Award for Best Animated Feature at the 75th Academy Awards in 2003.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] *Ice Age* would spawn a franchise and bolster Blue Sky into producing feature films and becoming a household name in feature animation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] From 2000 to 2010, 20th Century Fox was the international distributor for MGM/UA releases.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In the 1980s, 20th Century Fox – through a joint venture with CBS called CBS/Fox Video – had distributed certain UA films on video; thus UA has come full circle by switching to 20th Century Fox for video distribution.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] 20th Century Fox also makes money distributing films for small independent film companies.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 2006, 20th Century Fox terminated its production with Bad Hat Harry Productions for five years, because Bryan Singer left *X-Men: The Last Stand* to direct *Superman Returns* (2006) for Warner Bros.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Pictures, then he returned to produce the first film and direct its sequel in the prequel trilogy, starting in 2011.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In late 2006, Fox Atomic was started up under Fox Searchlight head Peter Rice and COO John Hegeman as a sibling production division under Fox Filmed Entertainment.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In early 2008, Atomic's marketing unit was transferred to Fox Searchlight and 20th Century Fox, when Hegeman moved to New Regency Productions.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After two middling successes and falling short with other films, the unit was shut down in April 2009.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The remaining films under its Atomic label in production and post-productions were transferred to 20th Century Fox and Fox Searchlight with Liebling overseeing them.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 2008, 20th Century Fox announced an Asian subsidiary, Fox STAR Studios, a joint venture with STAR TV, also owned by News Corporation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It was reported that Fox STAR would start by producing films for the Bollywood market, then expand to several Asian markets.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In the same year, Twentieth Century Fox started Fox International Productions, but the division was closed in 2017.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Chernin Entertainment was founded by Peter Chernin after he stepped down as president of 20th Century Fox's then-parent company News Corporation in 2009.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Chernin Entertainment's five-year first-look deal for the film and television was signed with 20th Century Fox and 20th Century Fox Television in 2009.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On June 28, 2012, Rupert Murdoch announced that News Corporation would be split into two publishing and media-oriented companies: a new News Corporation and 21st Century Fox, which operated the Fox Entertainment Group and 20th Century Fox.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Murdoch considered the name of the new company a way to maintain the 20th Century Fox heritage.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On August 20, 2012, 20th Century Fox entered a five-year distribution agreement with DreamWorks Animation, which began in 2013, after their distribution deal with Paramount Pictures ended with the 2012 release of *Rise of the Guardians*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] DreamWorks Animation's first film to be distributed under the new agreement was *The Croods*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox Stage Productions was formed in June 2013.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In August, the same year, 20th Century Fox started a theatrical joint venture with a trio of producers, both film and theater, Kevin McCollum, John Davis and Tom McGrath.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On September 20, 2017, Locksmith Animation formed a multi-year production deal with 20th Century Fox, who would distribute Locksmith's films under 20th Century Fox Animation, with Locksmith aiming to release a film every 12–18 months.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The first film to be released under the production company was *Ron's Gone Wrong*, which was released on October 22, 2021, by 20th Century Studios and was the only film to be released by the studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Technoprops, a VFX company that worked on *Avatar* and *The Jungle Book*, was purchased in April 2017 to operate as Fox VFX Lab.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Technoprops' founder Glenn Derry would continue to run the company as vice president of visual effect reporting to Gerard Bevan and John Kilkenny, VFX president.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On October 30, 2017, Vanessa Morrison was named president of a newly created 20th Century Fox division, Fox Family, reporting to the chairman & CEO and Vice Chairman of 20th Century Fox.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The family division would develop films that appeal to younger moviegoers and their parents both animated films and films with live-action elements.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Also, the division would oversee the studio's family animated television business, which produces holiday television specials based on existing film properties, and oversee feature film adaptation of its TV shows.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] To replace Morrison at Fox Animation, Andrea Miloro and Robert Baird were named co-presidents of 20th Century Fox Animation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] 20th Century Fox issued a default notice in regards to its licensing agreement for the under-construction 20th Century Fox World theme park in Malaysia by Genting Malaysia Bhd.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In November 2018 Genting Malaysia filed suit in response and included soon to be parent the Walt Disney Company.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On December 14, 2017, Disney announced plans to purchase most of 21st Century Fox, including 20th Century Fox, for $52.4 billion.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After a bid from Comcast (owner of NBCUniversal) for $65 billion, Disney counterbid with $71.3 billion.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On July 19, 2018, Comcast dropped out of the bid for 21st Century Fox in favor of Sky plc and Sky UK.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Eight days later, Disney and 21st Century Fox shareholders approved the merger between the two companies.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Various units were moved out from under 20th Century Fox at acquisition in months after the merger along with several rounds of layoffs.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The Fox Research Library was folded into the Walt Disney Archives and Walt Disney Imagineering Archives in January 2020.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The last film to use the "20th Century Fox" name was *Underwater*, which was released on January 10, 2020.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After the box office failures of films like *Dark Phoenix* and *Stuber*, Disney halted development on several projects, though films such as *Free Guy* and the *Avatar* sequels managed to continue production.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox's slate would be reduced to 10 films per year, half of them being made for the Hulu and then-upcoming Disney+ streaming services.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Projects from 20th Century Fox franchises such as *Home Alone*, *Cheaper by the Dozen*, *Night at the Museum*, *Diary of a Wimpy Kid*, and *Ice Age* were later announced for Disney+.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] These projects would later be fully revealed during Disney's Investor Day in December 2020 as feature films for the aforementioned streaming service.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The first of these projects was *Home Sweet Home Alone*, which was released on November 12, 2021.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On January 17, 2020, Disney renamed the studio to "20th Century Studios", which served to help avoid brand confusion with Fox Corporation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment distributes the films produced by 20th Century and Searchlight in home media under their respective labels.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The first film released by Disney under the studio's new name was *The Call of the Wild*, which was released on February 21, 2020.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Ferrari* (2019), among its four Academy Award nominations, earned the studio its first Best Picture nomination post-Disney acquisition.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In the same year, held-over production president Emma Watts left the company.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On March 12, 2020, Steve Asbell was named president, production of 20th Century Studios, while Morrison was named president, streaming, Walt Disney Studios Motion Picture Production to oversee live-action development and production of Walt Disney Pictures and 20th Century Studios for Disney+.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Philip Steuer will now lead physical and post-production and VFX, as president of production at Walt Disney Studios Motion Picture Production.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Randi Hiller will now lead casting as executive VP casting, overseeing both Walt Disney Pictures and 20th Century Studios.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Steuer has served as executive VP of physical production for Walt Disney Studios since 2015, and Hiller has led casting for Walt Disney Studios since 2011.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Both will dual-report to Asbell and Sean Bailey.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On February 9, 2021, Disney announced that Blue Sky Studios would shut down in April 2021, and that it would be succeeded by 20th Century Animation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] A spokesperson for the company explained that in light of the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic's continued economic impact on all of its businesses, it was no longer sustainable for them to run a third feature animation studio.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In addition, production on a film adaptation of the webcomic *Nimona*, originally scheduled to be released on January 14, 2022, was cancelled as a result of its closure.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The studio's film library and intellectual properties are retained by Disney via 20th Century Animation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Although Disney did not give an exact date as to when the studio would be closing down initially, former animator Rick Fournier confirmed on April 10 it was their last day of operation, three days after founder Chris Wedge released a farewell letter on social media.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] *Nimona* would be picked up by Annapurna Pictures in early 2022 for release on Netflix in 2023.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On November 22, 2021, Disney Media and Entertainment Distribution and WarnerMedia reached an agreement to allow select 20th Century Studios films be shared between Disney+, Hulu, and HBO Max through late 2022.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The new agreement negotiated by Gerard Devan and John Gelke is an amendment to the original agreement between 20th Century Fox and HBO that Disney inherited after its acquisition of Fox in 2019, and as such, is not expected to be renewed.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Following the end of the 20th Century-HBO deal, Disney planned to retain the 20th Century films on their own streaming platforms going forward after 2022.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The first film to this new strategy was *Ron's Gone Wrong*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Also in 2021, Disney had launched a video game based-studio 20th Century Games.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Similar to its predecessors—FoxNext, Fox Interactive and 20th Century Fox Games—it acts as a distributor and has partnered with other triple-A game studios.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Its first title was *Aliens: Fireteam Elite*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On February 8, 2022, Steven Spielberg's 2021 film version of *West Side Story*, among its seven Academy Award nominations, earned 20th Century Studios its first Best Picture nomination post-rebranding.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In March 2023, it was announced that Marvel Comics would be launching a 20th Century Studios imprint, which would release comics based on 20th Century franchises.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The first comic under the label would be a *Planet of the Apes* comic.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] On February 26, 2024, Walt Disney Pictures announced the immediate departure of its president, Sean Bailey, with Searchlight Pictures president David Greenbaum assuming his position.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Greenbaum would lead Walt Disney Pictures and co-lead 20th Century with Steve Asbell as president.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In April 2025, Disney announced that it would not renew its lease with Fox Corporation and that it would vacate the Fox Studio Lot in Century City at the end of 2025.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] As a result, 20th Century relocated to the Walt Disney Studios in Burbank.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] 20th Television is the television production division of 20th Century Studios.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It was known as 20th Century Fox Television until it adopted the 20th Television name in 2020.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The 20th Television name was already in use prior to 2020, as the original 20th Television was the studio's television syndication division until it was folded into Disney–ABC Domestic Television in 2020.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] During the mid-1950s, feature films were released to television in the hope that they would broaden sponsorship and help the distribution of network programs.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Blocks of one-hour programming of feature films to national sponsors on 128 stations were organized by 20th Century Fox and National Telefilm Associates.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] 20th Century Fox received 50% interest in the NTA Film Network after it sold its library to National Telefilm Associates.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] This gave 90 minutes of cleared time a week and syndicated feature films (under the package title "Premiere Performance") to 110 non-interconnected stations for sale to national sponsors.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox bought out the remaining assets of Four Star Television from Ronald Perelman's Compact Video in 1996.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The majority of Four Star Television's library of programs are controlled by 20th Television today.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] After Murdoch's numerous buyouts during the buyout era of the eighties, News Corporation had built up financial debts of $7 billion (much from Sky TV in the UK), despite the many assets that were held by NewsCorp.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The high levels of debt caused Murdoch to sell many of the American magazine interests he had acquired in the mid-1980s.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Between 1933 and 1937, a custom record label called *Fox Movietone* was produced starting at F-100 and running through F-136.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It featured songs from 20th Century Fox movies, first using material recorded and issued on Victor's Bluebird label and halfway through switched to material recorded and issued on ARC's dime store labels (Melotone, Perfect, etc.).
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] These scarce records were sold only at Fox Theaters.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The music arm of 20th Century Fox, 20th Century-Fox Records, was founded in 1958.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Fox Records was the 20th Century Fox's music arm since 1992 before being renamed to Fox Music in 2000.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It encompasses music publishing and licensing businesses, dealing primarily with Fox Entertainment Group's television and film soundtracks under license by Universal Music Group, EMI, PolyGram, Bertelsmann Music Group, Sony Music, and Warner Music Group.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It would also go defunct on January 17, 2020, and was subsequently folded into Hollywood Records.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The **Newman Scoring Stage**, named after composer Alfred Newman, is a large scoring studio located on the Fox Studio Lot, spanning almost 700 square meters, and is one of the largest music recording spaces in the world.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] It is also equipped with a 96 Channel AMS Neve 88RS-SP mixing console.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The *Twentieth Century Fox Presents* radio series were broadcast between 1936 and 1942.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] More often than not, the shows were a radio preview featuring a medley of the songs and soundtracks from the latest movie being released into the theaters, much like the modern-day movie trailers we now see on TV, to encourage folks to head down to their nearest Picture House.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The radio shows featured the original stars, with the announcer narrating a lead-up that encapsulated the performance.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] From its earliest ventures into movie production, Fox Film Corporation operated its own processing laboratories.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] The original lab was located in Fort Lee, New Jersey along with the studios.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] A lab was included with the new studio built in Los Angeles in 1916.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Freedman, the Fort Lee lab was moved into the new Fox Studios building in Manhattan in 1919.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In 1932, Freedman bought the labs from Fox for $2,000,000 to bolster what at that time was a failing Fox liquidity.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] He renamed the operation "DeLuxe Laboratories," which much later became Deluxe Entertainment Services Group.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] In the 1940s Freedman sold the labs back to what was then 20th Century Fox and remained as president into the 1960s.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p01] Under Freedman's leadership, DeLuxe added two more labs in Chicago and Toronto and processed film from studios other than Fox, such as UA and Universal.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] The 20th Century Fox production logo and fanfare originated as the logo of Twentieth Century Pictures and was adopted by 20th Century-Fox after the merger in 1935.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] It consists of a stacked block-letter three-dimensional, monolithic logotype (nicknamed "the Monument") surrounded by Art deco buildings and illuminated by searchlights.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] In the production logo that appears at the start of films, the searchlights are animated and the sequence is accompanied by a distinctive fanfare that was originally composed in 1933 by Alfred Newman.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] The original layout of the logo was designed by special effects animator and matte painting artist Emil Kosa Jr.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] In 1953, Rocky Longo, an artist at Pacific Title, was hired to recreate the original logo design for the new CinemaScope picture process.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] Longo tilted the "0" in "20th" to have the logo maintain proportions in the wider CinemaScope format.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] Alfred Newman also composed an extended version of the logo's fanfare to be heard during the CinemaScope logo that would follow after the Fox logo.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] Although the format had since declined, director George Lucas specifically requested that the CinemaScope version of the fanfare be used for the opening titles of *Star Wars* (1977).
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] Additionally, the film's main theme was composed by John Williams in the same key as the fanfare (B♭ major), serving as an extension to it of sorts.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] In 1981, the logo was altered with the re-straightening of the "0" in "20th".
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] It would later be re-recorded by David Newman in 1997 and again in 1998.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] In 2009, an updated logo created by Blue Sky Studios (a prototype version of the 2009 structure exists) debuted with the release of *Avatar*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] In 2013, the News Corporation byline was removed.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] On January 17, 2020, it was reported that Disney had begun to phase out the "Fox" name from the studio's branding as it is no longer tied to the current Fox Corporation, with 20th Century Fox and Fox Searchlight Pictures respectively renamed to 20th Century Studios and Searchlight Pictures.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] Branding elements associated with the studio, including the searchlights, monolith, and fanfare, will remain in use.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] The first film that carries the new 20th Century Studios name is *The Call of the Wild* (coincidentally the original film adaptation was the original Twentieth Century Pictures' final movie before its merger with Fox Film).
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] For the 20th Century Studios logo, its print logo debuted on a movie poster of *The New Mutants* while the on-screen logo debuted in a television advertisement for and the full version debuted on February 21, 2020, with the film *The Call of the Wild*.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] In 2020, 20th Century Studios logo was animated by Picturemill (the prototype version of the 2020 structure and the 2021 structure with the 2009 sky background exists and appeared in some of Picturemill's reels), while MOCEAN animated Searchlight Pictures logo, based on Blue Sky Studios' animation.
[src:d-vhs/20th-century-fox-p02] It features a different sky backdrop, the Los Angeles skyline is larger and more detailed, and the rest of the structure appears darker with more realistic lighting.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 Entertainment has offices in Los Angeles, New York, and Dallas.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] Wagner and Cuban co-own 2929 with Sky Hansen serving as managing director.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 Entertainment made several strategic acquisitions to assure that releases could be made available to any audience across a variety of platforms simultaneously.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] Wagner says that "ready availability of such infrastructure would be an operating advantage to both the circuit and the production company." Some titles would even see DVD releases alongside theatrical openings as early as 2007, through an early partnership with Netflix.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] An extensive catalogue of television and film rights were acquired with Rysher Entertainment in 2001, and 2929 would co-produce a newer version of *Star Search* which premiered in January 2003 on CBS (the original *Star Search* aired from 1983 to 1995).
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 Entertainment develops original feature and series through its production company 2929 Productions, and formerly through HDNet Films.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 Productions, LLC. was co-founded by Wagner and Cuban in 2003.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] The film and television studio selectively finances and develops feature films and series, often through partnerships with industry creators or entertainment companies.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 Productions is headed by Haley Jones.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] Previous studio leadership has included Ben Cosgrove (formerly of Paramount and Section Eight) and Marc Butan (MadRiver Pictures and formerly Lionsgate).
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] In 2005, 2929 Productions released *Good Night, And Good Luck.* with Warner Independent.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] The film uses a mix of archival footage and contemporary production to tell the story of the famed wartime reporter Edward Murrow (David Strathairn) and his historic "See it Now" broadcast criticizing Senator Joseph McCarthy and the Red Scare.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] To mitigate risks that could arise with a black-and-white feature film, Wagner engaged Jeff Skoll and his company Participant Media to produce *Good Night, And Good Luck*, which grossed over $30 million (USA) and was nominated for six Academy Awards, including Best Picture.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] HDNet Films, the motion picture division of the HDNet network (now AXS TV), produced lower budget movies in high definition.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] Originally formed in 2001 by Bill Banowsky and Eamonn Bowles, Magnolia Pictures is the home entertainment and theatrical distribution subsidiary of 2929.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] In November 2005 the company created Magnolia Home Entertainment to release its films over home video, with its first release being Alex Gibney's acclaimed doc, *Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room*.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] It is headed by entertainment industry vet and former head of home entertainment for Miramax, Randy Wells.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] Magnolia Pictures also provides its content through a curated streaming service, Magnolia Selects.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 also launched Truly Indie, an "innovative distribution program" for independent filmmakers.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 holds a significant interest in AXS TV, which Cuban originally co-founded in 2001 as the all-high definition cable channel HDNet (through AXS TV LLC, formerly HDNet, LLC).
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] HDNet Movies, a companion channel, shows movies in high definition.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 also owned Rysher Entertainment, a television syndication distributor with an extensive library of titles and syndication rights to TV shows like *Hogan's Heroes*, *Sex and the City* and *Star Search*.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] Rysher was later acquired by an investment company through Lakeshore Entertainment.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 acquired Landmark Theatres September 24, 2003.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] The chain was originally founded by Kim Jorgensen in 1974 and specialized in independent and foreign films.
[src:d-vhs/2929-entertainment] 2929 maintains an interest in Spotlight Cinema Networks, a cinema advertising company.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The 4K television market share increased as prices fell dramatically throughout 2013 and 2014.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The term **4K** is generic and refers to any resolution with a horizontal pixel count of approximately 4,000.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Several different 4K resolutions have been standardized by various organizations.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] 4K resolution is approximately 8 million pixels, which is 4 times as many as 1080p.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2005, Digital Cinema Initiatives (DCI), a prominent standards organization in the cinema industry, published the **Digital Cinema System Specification**.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This specification establishes standardized 2K and 4K container formats for digital cinema production, with resolutions of 2048 × 1080 and 4096 × 2160 respectively.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] 2K distributions can have a frame rate of either 24 or 48 FPS, while 4K distributions must have a frame rate of 24 FPS.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Some articles claim that the terms **2K** and **4K** were coined by DCI and refer exclusively to the 2K and 4K formats defined in the DCI standard.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] However, usage of these terms in the cinema industry predates the publication of the DCI standard, and they are generally understood as casual terms for any resolution approximately 2000 or 4000 pixels in width, rather than names for specific standard resolutions.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2007, the Society of Motion Picture and Television Engineers published *SMPTE ST 2036-1*, which defines parameters for two UHDTV systems called **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2**.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2012, the International Telecommunication Union, Radiocommunication Sector published Recommendation BT.2020, also known as the Ultra High Definition Television (UHDTV) standard.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] It adopts the same image parameters defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Although the UHDTV standard does not define any official names for the formats it defines, ITU typically uses the terms **4K**, **4K UHD**, or **4K UHDTV** to refer to the 3840 × 2160 system in public announcements and press releases (**8K** for the 7680 × 4320 system).
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In some of ITU's other standards documents, the terms **UHDTV1** and **UHDTV2** are used as shorthand.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In October 2012, the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) announced its definition of the term **Ultra High-Definition** (or **Ultra HD**) for use with marketing consumer display devices.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The CEA definition does allow manufacturers to use other terms—such as **4K**—alongside the Ultra HD logo.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Since the resolution in CEA's definition is only a minimum requirement, displays with higher resolutions such as 4096 × 2160 or 5120 × 2880 also qualify as "Ultra HD" displays, provided they meet the other requirements.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Some 4K resolutions, like 3840 × 2160, are often casually referred to as **2160p**.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The term **2160p** could be applied to any format with a height of 2160 pixels, but it is most commonly used in reference to the 4K UHDTV resolution of 3840 × 2160 due to its association with the well-known 720p and 1080p HDTV formats.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Although 3840 × 2160 is both a 4K resolution and a 2160p resolution, these terms cannot always be used interchangeably since not all 4K resolutions are 2160 pixels tall, and not all 2160p resolutions are ≈4000 pixels wide.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] However, some companies have begun using the term "4K" to describe devices with support for a 2160p resolution, even if it is not close to 4000 pixels wide.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] For example, many "4K" dash cams only support a resolution of 2880 × 2160 (4∶3); although this is a 2160p resolution, it is not a 4K resolution.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Conversely, Samsung released a 5120 × 2160 (64∶27) TV, but marketed it as a "4K" TV despite its 5K-class resolution.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2015, LG Display announced the implementation of a new technology called M+, which is the addition of white subpixels along with the regular RGB dots in their IPS panel technology.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The media and internet users later called this "RGBW" TVs because of the white sub pixel.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Most of the new M+ technology was employed on 4K TV sets, which led to a controversy after tests showed that the addition of a white subpixel replacing the traditional RGB structure would reduce the resolution by around 25%.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] After tests done by Intertek in which the technical aspects of LG M+ TVs were analyzed and they concluded that "the addressable resolution display is 2,880 X 2,160 for each red, green, blue", in other words, the LG TVs were technically 2.8K as it became known in the controversy.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This negatively impacts the rendering of text, making it a bit fuzzier, which is especially noticeable when a TV is used as a PC monitor.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2019, Sony was granted the CinemaWide trademark by the European Union Intellectual Property Office (EUIPO), in which the trademark covers 'Class 9' electronic devices, including smartphones.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Sony Xperia smartphones are the most widely known products that equipped with CinemaWide 4K display, such as Xperia 1, Xperia 1 II, Xperia 1 III, Xperia 1 IV and Xperia 1 V.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Video sharing website YouTube and the television industry have adopted 3840 × 2160 as their 4K standard.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] As of 2014, 4K content from major broadcasters remained limited.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] By late 2014, 4K content was becoming more widely available online, including on Apple TV, YouTube, Netflix, Hulu, and Amazon Prime Video.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] By 2013, some UHDTV models were available to general consumers in the range of US$600.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] As of 2015, prices on smaller computer and television panels had dropped below US$400.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] On March 26, 2013, the Advanced Television Systems Committee announced new proposals of a new standard called ATSC 3.0 which would implement UHD broadcasts at resolutions of up to 3840 × 2160 or 7680 × 4320.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The standard would also include framerates of up to 120 Hz, HEVC encoding, wide color gamut, as well as high dynamic range.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2014, the Digital Video Broadcasting Project released a new set of standards intended to guide the implementation of high-resolution content in broadcast television.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Dubbed **DVB-UHDTV**, it establishes two standards, known as **UHD-1** (for 4K content) and **UHD-2** (for 8K content).
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] These standards use resolutions of 3840 × 2160 and 7680 × 4320 respectively, with framerates of up to 60 Hz, color depth up to 10 bpc (30 bit/px), and HEVC encoding for transmission.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] DVB is currently focusing on the implementation of the UHD-1 standard.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] DVB finalized **UHD-1 Phase 2** in 2016, with the introduction of service by broadcasters expected in 2017.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] UHD-1 Phase 2 adds features such as high dynamic range (using HLG and PQ at 10 or 12 bits), wide color gamut (BT.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] As of February 2025, both YouTube and Vimeo support high-resolution video uploads, with maximum resolutions of 4096 × 2304 pixels (approximately 9.4 megapixels) and 4096 × 2160 pixels (approximately 8.8 megapixels), respectively.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The growing availability of 4K content across streaming platforms like Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, and YouTube has made it more accessible to consumers.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Vimeo's 4K content is currently limited to mostly nature documentaries and tech coverage.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC or H.265) facilitates streaming of 4K content at bitrates between 20 and 30 Mbit/s, offering efficient compression without significant quality loss.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In January 2014, Naughty America launched the first adult video service streaming in 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In February 2025, Super Bowl LIX was broadcast in 4K resolution with Dolby Vision HDR and Dolby Atmos sound for the first time.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Fox aired the game, and it was also available for free streaming in 4K on Tubi, marking a significant milestone in sports broadcasting.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The first mobile phones to be able to record at 2160p (3840 × 2160) were released in late 2013, including the Samsung Galaxy Note 3, which is able to record 2160p at 30 frames per second.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In the year 2014, the OnePlus One was released with the option to record DCI 4K (4096 × 2160) at 24 frames per second, as well as LG G3 and Samsung Galaxy Note 4 with optical image stabilization.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In the year 2015, Apple announced the iPhone 6s was released with the 12 megapixel camera that has the option to record 4K at 25 or 30 frames per second.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In the years 2017 and 2018, mobile phone chipsets reached sufficient processing power that mobile phone vendors started releasing mobile phones that allow recording 2160p footage at 60 frames per second for a smoother and more realistic appearance.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] iMac with Retina Display (2014) is one of the earliest computers that utilise 4K widescreen.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 1981, the NEC μPD7220 computer graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×1024p (progressive scan) or 4096×2048i (interlaced).
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 1984, Hitachi's ARTC HD63484 graphics processor supported monochrome resolutions up to 4096×2048p (progressive scan) or 4096×4096i (interlaced), targeted at the bit-mapped desktop publishing market.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2000, JVC introduced the first 4K digital cinema video projector using D-ILA technology.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The first commercially available 4K camera for cinematographic purposes was the Dalsa Origin, released in 2003.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Sony began offering 4K digital cinema projectors in 2004.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] 4K digital projectors were introduced to movie theaters in 2005, but most theaters continued using analog movie projectors until 4K digital projectors eventually replaced them by 2011.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] 4K streaming technology was developed during the mid-to-late 2000s by several research groups in universities around the world, such as University of California, San Diego, CALIT2, Keio University and Naval Postgraduate School.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] They realized several demonstrations in venues such as IGrid in 2004 and CineGrid.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] YouTube began supporting 4K for video uploads in 2010 as a result of leading manufacturers producing 4K cameras.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Users could view 4K video by selecting "Original" from the quality settings until December 2013, when the 2160p option appeared in the quality menu.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In November 2013, YouTube began to use the VP9 video compression standard, saying that it was more suitable for 4K than High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC).
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Google, which owns YouTube, developed VP9.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The first 4K home theater projector was released by Sony in 2012.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Despite this, as of 2023, there are not many finished films with 4K resolution.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Even for movies and TV shows shot using 6K or 8K cameras, almost all finished films are edited in HD resolution and enlarged to fit a 4K format.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Sony is one of the leading studios promoting UHDTV content, as of 2013 offering a little over 70 movie and television titles via digital download to a specialized player that stores and decodes the video.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The large files (≈40 GB), distributed through consumer broadband connections, raise concerns about data caps.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2014, Netflix began streaming *House of Cards*, *Breaking Bad*, and "some nature documentaries" at 4K to compatible televisions with an HEVC decoder.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Most 4K televisions sold in 2013 did not natively support HEVC, with most major manufacturers announcing support in 2014.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Amazon Studios began shooting their full-length original series and new pilots with 4K resolution in 2014.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] They are now currently available through Amazon Video.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In March 2016 the first players and discs for Ultra HD Blu-ray—a physical optical disc format supporting 4K resolution and high-dynamic-range video (HDR) at 60 frames per second—were released.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] On August 2, 2016, Microsoft released the Xbox One S, which supports 4K streaming and has an Ultra HD Blu-ray disc drive, but does not support 4K gaming.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] On November 10, 2016, Sony released the PlayStation 4 Pro, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though many games use checkerboard rendering or are upscaled 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] On November 7, 2017, Microsoft released the Xbox One X, which supports 4K streaming and gaming, though not all games are rendered at native 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Though the price of home cinema viewing devices began to drop rapidly from 2013, the digital video projector market saw limited expansion as very few manufacturers had fully 4K-capable lineups.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Native 4K projectors remained priced in the five-figure range well into 2015, only falling below US$10,000 later that year.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Sony was the sole major manufacturer offering a comprehensive 4K projection solution as of 2015.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Critics argue that, at typical direct-view panel sizes and viewing distances, the extra pixels of 4K are unnecessary for normal human vision.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In contrast, home cinema projectors use larger screens without necessarily increasing the viewing distance to match the scale.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This technology reached its fourth generation in 2016.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] JVC applied this technology to create an 8K flight simulation system for Boeing, meeting the visual acuity limits of 20/25.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The first pixel-shifted 4K UHD projectors adopted by the market are Optoma, BenQ, Dell, et al., for those adopt a 2718×1528 pixel structure.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The amount of data these projectors process is true 4K, but they overlap the pixels, which is what pixel shifting is.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In fact, each of those pixels is far larger.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In fact, each one has 50% more area than true 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This way, they project a pixel and shift it up to the right by a half diameter and project it again with modified data—the second pixel overlaid on the first.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This would result in adjacent red and green pixels effectively forming yellow, with a fringe on one side of red, on the other of green—except that the fringe takes on another color as the next line of pixels overlaps too.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] 4K UHD or 1080p pixel shifting cannot reveal the fine detail of a true 4K projector such as those Sony ships in the business, education, and home markets.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] While projecting UHD, it might look as though the pixel structures would have 1/4 the area of 1080p; it just doesn't happen with pixel shifting.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] That much resolution is only carried by a true 4K projector.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This is why "true" 4K costs so much more than 4K UHD projectors that have more or less similar feature sets.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] They produce smaller pixels, finer resolution—no loss of detail or color from the overlapping pixels.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This is in stark contrast to the small variation in the aspect ratio difference, which would be capable of being noticeable in a few companies, such as Kaleidescape, offering media servers that enable 4K UHD Blu-ray movies with a wide dynamic range in a home theater.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In November 2014, American satellite provider DirecTV (owned by AT&T) became the first pay-TV provider to offer access to 4K content, although limited to selected video-on-demand films.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In August 2015, British sports network BT Sport launched a 4K feed, with its first broadcast being the 2015 FA Community Shield football match.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Two production units were used, producing the traditional broadcast in high-definition, and a separate 4K broadcast.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] As the network did not want to mix 4K footage with upconverted HD footage, this telecast did not feature traditional studio segments at pre-game or half-time, but those hosted from the stadium by the match commentators using a 4K camera.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] BT envisioned that if viewers wanted to watch studio analysis, they would switch to the HD broadcast and then back for the game.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Footage was compressed using H.264 encoders and transmitted to BT Tower, where it was then transmitted back to BT Sport studios and decompressed for distribution, via 4K-compatible BT TV set-top boxes on an eligible BT Infinity internet plan with at least a 25 Mbit/s connection.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In late 2015 and January 2016, three of Canada's television providers – including Quebec-based Vidéotron, Ontario-based Rogers Cable, and Bell Fibe TV, announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes that can stream 4K content to subscribers over gigabit internet service.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Bell Media announced via its TSN division a slate of 4K telecasts to begin on January 20, 2016, including selected Toronto Raptors games and regional NHL games.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] On January 14, 2016, in cooperation with BT Sport, Sportsnet broadcast the first ever NBA game produced in 4K – a Toronto Raptors/Orlando Magic game at O2 Arena in London, England.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] On January 20, also during a Raptors game, TSN presented the first live 4K telecast produced in North America.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Three days later, Sportsnet presented the first NHL game in 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] For the opening game of the 2016 Toronto Blue Jays season, Dome constructed "Trillium" – a production truck integrating both 4K and 1080i high-definition units.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Bell Media's CTV also broadcast the 2016 Juno Awards in 4K as the first awards show presented in the format.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In February 2016, Spanish-language Univision trialed 4K by producing a closed-circuit TV broadcast of a football friendly between the national teams of Mexico and Senegal from Miami (America) in the format.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The broadcast was streamed privately to several special viewing locations.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Univision aimed to develop a 4K streaming app to publicly televise the final of Copa América Centenario in 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In March 2016, DirecTV and CBS Sports announced that they would produce the "Amen Corner" supplemental coverage from the Masters golf tournament in 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In late 2016, Telus TV announced that they would begin to offer 4K compatible set-top boxes.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] After having trialed the technology in limited matches at the 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup, and the 2014 FIFA World Cup (via private tests and public viewings in the host city of Rio de Janeiro), the 2018 FIFA World Cup was the first FIFA World Cup in which all matches were produced in 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Host Broadcasting Services stated that at least 75% of the broadcast cut on each match would come from 4K cameras (covering the majority of main angles), with instant replays and some camera angles being upconverted from 1080p sources.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] These broadcasts were made available from selected rightsholders, such as the BBC in the UK, and selected television providers in the United States.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Technical limitations in distributing 4K broadcasts (including the increased cost of 4K-compatible production equipment) have led to some broadcasters deciding against the format in favour of emphasizing 1080p/HDR broadcasts instead.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] After having broadcast UEFA Euro and the Champions League final in the format, UEFA discontinued 4K coverage for both in 2024, as broadcasters elected to put resources behind HDR and other on-air features instead.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Some U.S. broadcasters, such as CBS Sports, Fox Sports, and USA Network have broadcast events promoted as having "4K" feeds, but are actually 1080p/HDR broadcasts upconverted to 4K.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] For the 2024 Summer Olympics, USA Network's "4K" coverage was sourced from host broadcaster Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS) in 4K, but downconverted to 1080p when received by NBC Sports' studios, and then upconverted to 4K for distribution.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 is the dominant 4K resolution in the consumer media and display industries.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This is the resolution of the UHDTV1 format defined in SMPTE ST 2036–1, as well as the 4K UHDTV format defined by ITU-R in Rec.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] 2020, and is also the minimum resolution for CEA's definition of **Ultra HD** displays and projectors.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The resolution of 3840 × 2160 was also chosen by the DVB project for their 4K broadcasting standard, UHD-1.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This resolution has an aspect ratio of 16∶9, with 8,294,400 total pixels.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] It is exactly double the horizontal and vertical resolution of 1080p (1920 × 1080) for a total of 4 times as many pixels, and triple the horizontal and vertical resolution of 720p (1280 × 720) for a total of 9 times as many pixels.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] It is sometimes referred to as "2160p", based on the naming patterns established by the previous 720p and 1080p HDTV standards.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In 2013, televisions capable of displaying UHD resolutions were seen by consumer electronics companies as the next trigger for an upgrade cycle after a lack of consumer interest in 3D television.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This resolution is used mainly in digital cinema production, and has a total of 8,847,360 pixels with an aspect ratio of 256∶135 (≈19∶10).
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] It was standardized as the resolution of the 4K container format defined by Digital Cinema Initiatives in the Digital Cinema System specification, and is the native resolution of all DCI-compliant 4K digital projectors and monitors.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The DCI specification allows several different resolutions for the content inside the container, depending on the desired aspect ratio.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The DCI 4K standard has twice the horizontal and vertical resolution of DCI 2K (2048 × 1080), with four times as many pixels overall.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Digital movies made in 4K may be produced, scanned, or stored in a number of other resolutions depending on what storage aspect ratio is used.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] In the digital cinema production chain, a resolution of 4096 × 3112 is often used for acquiring "open gate" or anamorphic input material, a resolution based on the historical resolution of scanned Super 35 mm film.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] The main advantage of recording video at the 4K standard is that fine spatial detail is resolved well.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Individual still frames extracted from 3840×2160-pixel video footage can act as 8.3 megapixel still photographs, while only 2.1 megapixels at 1080p and 0.9 megapixels at 720p.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] If the final video resolution is reduced to 2K from a 4K recording, more detail is apparent than would have been achieved from a native 2K recording.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Increased fineness and contrast is then possible with output to DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Some cinematographers record at 4K with the Super 35 film format to offset any resolution loss that may occur during video processing.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Many consumer electronics such as mobile phones store video footage in Y′CBCR format with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling, which records color information at only one quarter the resolution as the brightness information.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] For 3840 × 2160 video, this means that the color information is only stored at 1920 × 1080.
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] Consumer cameras and mobile phones record 2160p footage at much higher bit rates (usually 50 to 100 Mbit/s) than 1080p (usually 10 to 30 Mbit/s).
[src:d-vhs/4k-resolution] This higher bit rate reduces the visibility of compression artifacts, even if viewed on monitors with a lower resolution than 2160p.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Unlike analog-based VHS and S-VHS, D-VHS records video digitally using MPEG-2 compression and stores it in an MPEG transport stream, a format also used in DVDs and digital television broadcasts.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The format was standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission as IEC 60774-5.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] JVC also developed **D-Theater**, a proprietary variant of D-VHS used for prerecorded high-definition movies.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] D-Theater tapes featured studio-released content in 720p or 1080i resolution, offering a home viewing experience similar to early Blu-ray and HD DVD formats.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] However, the system required compatible D-VHS players and included copy protection, which limited its adoption.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Existing tape media is bulky and more expensive than hard drives.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Another alternative is a lengthy transfer to a computer for viewing.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Finally, since machines are no longer manufactured, maintenance of current recorders may prove difficult.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] D-VHS's primary advantage is that it is still the best way to archive *encrypted* high definition material from cable programming in the US.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Cable, satellite companies, TiVo, and PCs equipped with cable card tuners all offered high-definition digital video recorders, but archival has proven to be an obstacle, as proprietary boxes have restrictions on moving encrypted content.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Outside of D-VHS, only HD capture devices that use an analog conversion process, such as the Hauppauge HD PVR, have enabled removal of encrypted content off many of the above proprietary boxes.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] This uses an analog conversion process, producing slightly degraded but still high definition grade recordings.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] D-VHS, on the other hand, does not need to take advantage of this so-called "analog hole", since D-VHS makes possible a pure bit-for-bit recording with no conversion necessary.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] This is made possible by compliance with CCI flag values carried by the digital streams, wherein only D-VHS is allowed to digitally move recordings of content originally flagged as Copy Once from a DVR device and onto a D-VHS tape.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] This programming that complies with the CCI flags then marks such material on the tape such that no second generation copies can be made from the tape itself, though additional copies can still be made directly from the original DVR unit to additional tapes.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Monthly rental fees to cable, TiVo, and satellite were also less with D-VHS.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The only PAL D-VHS model sold in Europe was the JVC HM-DR10000, also sold as the Philips VR-20D, and was standard definition only.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] This model was not a bitstream recorder, although it did have a FireWire input.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Instead it is best thought of as a digital recorder for traditional analog inputs such as domestic analog TV and digiboxes for digital broadcasts.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The deck was able to record D-VHS signals onto S-VHS tapes, which made it a cost-effective source of high quality domestic recordings (the US version also allows use of cheaper S-VHS media).
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Pictures were noticeably superior to S-VHS and were essentially transparent when compared to an off-air source.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Using the LS3 mode, approximately 17.25 hours of digital video could be stored on a S-VHS E-240.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The deck's biggest shortcomings were the lack of a DV output and, perhaps more crucially, the lack of RGB input via the SCART connector.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] NTSC versions had component video outputs.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] D-VHS VCRs can record at multiple speeds.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] "HS" is "High Speed", "STD" is "Standard" and "LS" is "Low Speed"; where LS3 and LS5 represent 3 and 5 times the standard length of tape, respectively.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] High-definition content such as 1920x1080 or 1280x720 is typically stored at 28.2 Mbit/s (HS speed).
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Standard-definition content such as 720x576 (720x480) can be stored at bit rates from 14.1 Mbit/s down to 2.8 Mbit/s (STD, LS3, LS5 speeds).
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The quality of STD speed is superior to the average DVD, since this speed has a much higher bitrate (approximately 14 versus 5 Mbit/s average) and suffers few compression artifacts.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The LS3 speed is roughly equal to an amateur DVD with some visible artifacts in high-action scenes (4.7 Mbit/s), and LS5 appears similar to a medium-quality video download (2.8 Mbit/s).
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] JVC's HM-DH40000U and SR-VD400U were the only units to support LS5 recording.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] As a result of all these different speeds, the tape labels are a bit confusing for the consumer.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] D-VHS was originally a standard definition format that recorded at the STD speed.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] When High Definition recording and HS speed was later introduced, it required twice the amount of tape.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] For this reason, a DF-240 will record 240 minutes of standard definition, and 240/2 = 120 minutes of high definition.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] When reviewing the table, note that the digital speeds HS and STD are equivalent to the older analog speeds SP and LP.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] There is also an additional speed called LS7.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] In 2002, prerecorded D-VHS cassettes were sold under the brand name D-Theater in the US.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] While D-Theater is a D-VHS tape, it is incompatible with D-VHS decks not bearing the D-Theater logo.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] They provide content in both 720p and 1080i as well as at least one Dolby Digital audio track.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Supported films studios include 20th Century Fox, Artisan Entertainment, DreamWorks, and Universal Pictures.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] D-Theater does have region code restrictions.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] There are 3 known regions; 1 for the US, 2 for Japan, and 3 for South Korea.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] There has never been a D-Theater video release in region 2 or 3.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Region code hacks for Japanese decks have been performed to support playback of US titles.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The last film available was 20th Century Fox's *I, Robot*.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] This title was a surprise to many as there were no prior announcements nor any indication that the title was available.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] It was originally available only on JVC's D-VHS store in late 2004 and no other distributor had it (not even Fox itself).
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] A couple of weeks later they started trickling out to more distributors after much delay and confusion about its existence.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Predator* was announced to retailers as also being released on the same day as *I, Robot*, but Fox later announced that *Alien vs.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Predator* was never shipped to retailers.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Most tapes have built-in copy protection mechanism (DTCP, also known as "5c") (copy never) that disables copying via FireWire.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] HDNet productions and 2929 Entertainment via Magnolia Entertainment did provide some of their original content on D-VHS but without copy protection.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Many of the tapes have an introduction by owner Mark Cuban encouraging the viewer to make copies of the program in order to help distribute them.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Additional tracks may be included on D-Theater in other sound formats such as DTS.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] However, only the newest D-VHS players, like the JVC HM-DH40000, HM-DH5U, HM-DT100U, and Marantz MV-8300, include alternate audio track capabilities.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] There are technical issues with compatibility between recordings from Mitsubishi and JVC D-VHS decks.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] PAL and NTSC recordings are also incompatible.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Very few models were available to the world market and sales of this format have been weak; correspondingly, prices remained high for both VCRs and media, contributing to low demand.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] In 2000, Sony arranged with JVC to manufacture D-VHS VCRs under the Sony label, marking one of the first collaborations between the two former rivals.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The lack of consumer knowledge of D-VHS's advantages and capabilities as well as input limitations led to its eventual demise.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] The introduction in 2006 of Blu-ray and HD-DVD rendered the format abandoned.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] There has been no small-format version of D-VHS equivalent to VHS-C; JVC, the originator of the format, chose to use MiniDV for its digital camcorder lines, and since 2005 has also expanded into tapeless camcorder designs based on hard drive storage (the Everio line).
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] JVC does market the Digital-S format for professional use; while the tapes and technology used are superficially similar to D-VHS tapes, the underlying data format is based on the DV codec and the media formulation is drastically different.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Sony's MicroMV format uses the same codec as D-VHS.
[src:d-vhs/d-vhs] Therefore, D-VHS capture software can also be used to transfer MicroMV tapes.
